article.headline: Detroit extends Eastern Conference lead to 3 games
article.linkText: Cash scores 25 to lead Shock past Mystics
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Swin Cash wanted to make up for a poor performance earlier this week. She did just that Sunday, scoring 25 points as the Detroit Shock beat the Washington Mystics 81-71. Cash went 3-of-14 and scored 10 points in a 67-61 loss to Charlotte on Thursday. "I wasn't happy with my performance against Charlotte, so I wanted to play a good game tonight," Cash said. "Nothing can make up for that loss, but this game helps us get our focus back." Detroit coach Bill Laimbeer expected a big game from his captain. "We knew this was coming -- the coaches talked about it before the game," he said. "That game in Charlotte hurt Swin's pride, so we knew she was going to pick it up tonight." The Shock have won five of six and extended their lead in the Eastern Conference to three games over idle Charlotte. Washington has lost four in a row, and is one game ahead of Phoenix for the league's worst record. "It has been one of those years for us," Chamique Holdsclaw said. "Players have been injured and everybody has been inconsistent. We just can't put it together." Deanna Nolan added 16 points for Detroit and Kedra Holland-Corn had 12 off the bench. Holdsclaw led all scorers with 27 points, while Ashja Jones added 17. Detroit held a 41-39 lead at halftime, thanks to 11 points from Nolan. Holdsclaw had 12 for the Mystics. Washington kept the game close until Detroit took advantage of several turnovers to put together a 12-0 run. Ruth Riley had six of the points and Cash added four as the Shock took a 60-47 lead with 11:23 to play. Washington's pressure defense allowed the Shock to score just two points in the next six minutes, allowing the Mystics to cut the margin to 62-56 with five minutes left. "I don't think it was their press that hurt us -- it was just us going to sleep," Laimbeer said. "We knew we had a little bit of a comfort zone tonight, and we used all of it." Washington got as close as 66-62, but Ford's three-point play gave the Shock a little breathing room. After a miss by Coco Miller, Holdsclaw fouled Nolan. She made both free throws to put Detroit up 71-62 with 2:41 left. The Mystics narrowed the gap to five, but Holland-Corn's 3-pointer put the game away. "You can't allow a 12-0 run like that if you want to stay in the game," Washington coach Marianne Stanley said. "After that, we had to scramble. I'm proud of the fact that we fought all the way to the end, but getting that far behind meant we needed to use a lot of energy to try to catch up." Game notes
The Shock activated Astou Ndiaye-Diatta from the injured list before the game, and put Petra Ujhelyi (back spasms) on the list. Ndiaye-Diatta, Detroit's career scoring and rebounding leader, gave birth to triplets in April. She played three scoreless minutes in the first half. ... Detroit needs two more wins to tie the franchise record of 17, set in its first season.
